@page "/concepts/bootstrap-data-api"

<DocHeadContent CanonicalRelativeUrl="/concepts/bootstrap-data-api" />

<DocHeading Level="1" Title="Using Bootstrap's native data APIs directly" />
<p>
	Bootstrap's declarative <code>data-bs-*</code> attributes work in Blazor markup as-is — the Bootstrap JavaScript bundle
	listens for them on the document, so no component wrapper, JS interop, or C# state is required.
	A typical use case is Bootstrap 6's <a href="https://v6-dev--twbs-bootstrap.netlify.app/docs/6.0/components/toggler/">Toggler</a>
	(<code>data-bs-toggle="toggler"</code>), which toggles a class or attribute on the trigger element or on a
	<code>data-bs-target</code> on each click. Because it is handled entirely by Bootstrap's JavaScript,
	it also works under static server-side rendering, where no interactivity is available.
</p>
<Demo Type="typeof(BootstrapDataApi_Demo_Toggler)" />
<p>
	The library intentionally provides no <code>HxToggler</code> wrapper component: the plugin is stateless, so there is no state
	to synchronize with your C# code. We wrap Bootstrap plugins only where the component holds state your application needs to
	read or drive (e.g. <a href="/components/@nameof(HxCollapse)">@nameof(HxCollapse)</a> with its expanded state and events,
	or <a href="/components/@nameof(HxDialog)">@nameof(HxDialog)</a> with its show/hide lifecycle).
</p>
